<br>
My theory is that a successful taunt DOES indeed put you at hatetop+1. That doesnt mean that the next time the other guy swings it will necessarily turn on him, that depends on the AI.<br>
<br>
For instance I could easily imagine the NPC AI target selection pseudo code looking like this:<br>
<br>
PlayerTop = Hatelist.first();<br>
If PlayerTop.Hate &gt; CurrentTarget.Hate+100 then SwitchTarget(PlayerTop)<br>
<br>
IE, the AI might be coded so that an NPC will only switch to a new target once a target with +100 or more hate OVER the current target is found(to prevent excessive target switching between melees using same type of weaponry)<br>
<br>
IF that is how it works, it would also be a really good argument for why you should keep mashing that taunt button when you are MT'ing during a bossmob fight.. Because that wizard might be a yourhate+98, ie just below the threshold where the mob will switch target. A succesfull taunt in that case would then net you +99 hate, even though you are already tanking.<br>
<br>
This is of course just a theory, and kinda hard to test unless you have access to two highlevel SKs and devise some tests using their +hate spells. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rani>rani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif" BORDER=0> at: 3/12/03 10:19:27 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tashant>Tashant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/12/03 10:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3015.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The taunt button, an anecdotal view.</span><hr size=1> I am going to have to agree with rani. For instance, try killing a named mob that slows, or stuns. Somehow I manage to keep agro even though I'm doing 0 damage, even if I'm stunned for 90% of the fight. I believe raid mobs have a formula like  <br>
<br>
PlayerTop = Hatelist.first();<br>
If PlayerTop.Hate &gt; CurrentTarget.Hate+1000 then SwitchTarget(PlayerTop)<br>
<br>
But this doesn't explain how a tank can taunt, and then get agro off said mob. This also brings many questions with how AE taunt works, does it not give the user highest person's agro +1, but rather just changes who is on the &quot;Hatelist.first()&quot;<br>
